post_text:
The coaches/representatives met tonight regarding the softball league. It was the decision of the league to cancel the 2020 season. As much as this breaks my heart, we want our kids to be safe with all the uncertainty that is going on. I will miss the opportunity to share my love of softball with them. This would have been Reagan’s last year of softball and Abigail’s second to last year, so I understand that this isn’t fair. Use this opportunity to go outside and play softball with your girls, I will miss seeing their faces. If possible,
we may try to have a softball camp in late July or August. Take care and be safe!

Coach Kelly

If you feel so moved please drive by and give a honk to show your support. Lights will shine until 10:30 PM. Feel free to share the event!

Summer Baseball/ Softball
We are still trying to have a baseball/softball season this summer. We will not be able to start in May due to social distancing. The M.t Vernon baseball association is going to try to have a season, even if it is short. More information will be available after we meet at the end of May. We want you to be able to sign-up for baseball/softball when and if we can have a short season. Please, contact Darcy Deinert at 770-8629 if you have questions about baseball and Kelly Rus at 770-0990 if you have any questions about softball. Watch the school website and city of Mt. Vernon facebook page for sign-up information and updates. Stay healthy!
Darcy Deinert
Mt. Vernon School

post_text: If you have not heard by now the Gov. has asked schools to remain closed until May 1st. We will continue with the E-learning already established expectations and procedures. We will be sending info on times for exchange of learning packets similar to what we did on Sunday. We are encouraged by the student engagement to this point. This is going to be our required delivery of education for the next month. Assignments are not optional or a choice. We will be taking grades moving forward. We have to remain accountable to the State DOE and we expect the students to engage in the learning process to the best of their ability. Please spread the word that we will now be serving Breakfast and Lunch for all students FREE OF CHARGE!! The pick-up time remains the same. The breakfast received will be for the next day so only one trip is needed. Thanks for all you are doing to help with your children's education. We so desperately want to be back in school as we know you all would prefer. Please remain patient. We all can get through it together. Stay tuned. Gods Blessings to all!

post_text: School Closure Alert: Please be advised that due to the Governor's strong recommendation that schools close all next week the Mount Vernon School Dist will comply with the Governor's office. We are asking that all students, parents, and public avoid using school facilities all next week so we can perform the "deep cleaning" that is also being recommended. There is also no outside use of any district facilities by any persons, organizations, or groups. Staff will be meeting on Monday to work on our plan/delivery model for instruction in the event that forced closures continue. We apologize for the inconvenience for this disruption of services. Please stay tuned next week for further up to date information.

post_text: Congratulations to the Mount Vernon Jazz Band and Jazz Choir students for their fantastic performances at the Lewis & Clark Jazz Festival in Sioux City today. Jazz Band took 4th place amongst elite competition in class 1A and performed very well. Jazz Choir took 1st place in class 1A and Kennedy Mayclin was awarded the overall outstanding soloist of the class! Mount Vernon was the only school of the day to perform for BOTH Jazz Band AND Jazz Choir. Congratulations to a great bunch of students!

post_text:
Ending the Silence Program

Mt. Vernon School District is hosting an “Ending the Silence” program this Friday, October 18th. “Ending the Silence” is sponsored by the National Alliance on Mental Illness (NAMI) and is designed for middle and high school students, school staff, and parents or guardians of middle or high school aged youth. During the presentation, audiences learn about the signs and symptoms of mental health conditions, how to recognize the early warning signs and the importance of acknowledging those warning signs.

Parents and community members are invited and encouraged to attend either presentation. Times are listed below.

10:30-11:20 Middle School Presentation (in gym)

11:50-12:40 High School Presentation (in gym)

post_text:
Operation Overload News Release

Mt. Vernon K-12 students will have the privilege of meeting Amber Hulse, the reigning Miss South Dakota, on Wednesday, October 9th. She will be spending the day at school to present her platform, “Operation Overload,” to 9-12 students. She will also read a book to the K-3 students and give a motivational presentation to upper elementary and middle school students.

The purpose of Operation Overload is to get targeted information to high school students about post-secondary education and other career options available after graduation. Ms. Hulse hopes this presentation will help students learn how to battle the overload of information they receive while trying to make postsecondary and career decisions, so they are prepared to make smart, sound choices for their futures. If you would like to learn more about her platform, visit www.operationoverload.org

The Salvation Army dropped off about 20 flood kits at the church. The kits contain Pine-Sol, bleach cleaner, gloves, mop, squeegee, broom, breathing mask, and a brush.

If you need one stop by and take one. They are right inside the side door of the church and the door is open.

The Salvation Army is also planning on offering a hot meal to anyone this evening. Will post more details when I know them.

SDPB Sports
November 13, 2018 at 6:27 PM ·

Since 1999, Darcy Deinert has been coaching volleyball in Mount Vernon. Now in a co-op with Plankinton, she recorded her 400th career win this season.

Even though Mount Vernon/Plankinton fell short of the state tournament in 2018, Deinert is considered one of the best, and most respected, high school volleyball coaches in South Dakota.
